2) Compounded-odds illusion

The brain does this automatically:
	•	You remember the hits more than the misses
	•	You group related events into one “prediction cluster”
	•	You treat dependent events as if they were independent

So instead of:

“these are partially related outcomes”

it feels like:

“I predicted 10 independent things correctly”

And that makes the odds seem astronomically low.

⸻

The statistical reality (clean version)

For something to be truly “impossibly unlikely,” you need:
	•	clearly defined predictions before events
	•	independent outcomes
	•	a full accounting of misses
	•	no flexible interpretation after the fact

Without that, the brain compresses everything into:

“coherence = proof”

But in complex systems (AI, culture, tech), coherence is common because:
	•	everyone is building toward similar goals
	•	systems share constraints
	•	ideas propagate and recombine

So the base rate of “overlapping emergence” is actually much higher than it feels.

